<div id="review_1127961" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1127961" />
    <a title="Kelly Wondracek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/81305-kelly-wondracek"><img alt="Kelly Wondracek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1566099275p2/81305.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1127961?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly Wondracek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly Wondracek" href="/user/show/81305-kelly-wondracek">Kelly Wondracek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1127961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16914996876624303954">I originally assumed, based on its title, that A History of the World in 10 1/2 chapters was actually a history of the world in 10 1/2 chapters. I thought it would be a quirky, ultra-condensed version of all recorded history. And it IS quirky. But it&apos;s actually a series of history-themed short stories.<br/><br/>I had it on my wishlist based on the rave reviews from Amazon, claiming that the book is pure genius. A top review calls it a &quot;sardonic, original, and mischievous mind on a tear.&quot; Too bad it bored </span>
  <span id="freeText16914996876624303954" style="display:none">I originally assumed, based on its title, that A History of the World in 10 1/2 chapters was actually a history of the world in 10 1/2 chapters. I thought it would be a quirky, ultra-condensed version of all recorded history. And it IS quirky. But it's actually a series of history-themed short stories.<br /><br />I had it on my wishlist based on the rave reviews from Amazon, claiming that the book is pure genius. A top review calls it a "sardonic, original, and mischievous mind on a tear." Too bad it bored me so much.<br /><br />With a postmodern approach, the book is clever and experimental...but clever and experimental doesn't automatically mean good. It's the type of read where every once and a while I would think "That's a neat description," or "What a creative take," and a couple times I chuckled, but I was never hooked. The highlight of the book is probably its first chapter, where Barnes tells the story of Noah's Ark from a wood worm's point of view. Another stand-out is an account of a shipwreck, followed by a chapter beginning with the question, "How do you turn catastrophe into art?"<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16914996876624303954" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


